<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>put cash on the barrelhead • put cash on the line</xh5><p> <i>put cash on the barrelhead</i>—(also: lay cash on the barrelhead) pay money at the time of the transaction: There was a time when, if a person got sick, he went to his trusted family doctor, and <u>put cash on the barrelhead</u>.</p><p> <i>put cash on the line</i>—(also: lay cash on the line) allocate money; make a financial commitment: Their decision to <u>put cash on the line</u> is a strong vote of confidence in the foundation being laid for America’s recovery.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>put it on the line</b>—(coll.) speak out firmly and frankly (also: lay it on the line): She was very mad. She <u>put it on the line</u> and we have no doubt about what she meant.</p> </entry>
